It is a fact that has long frustrated doctors and their patients: Up to 20 percent of women who suffer heart attacks and other coronary problems had no obvious risk factors - no high blood pressure or elevated cholesterol.
In an editorial accompanying the study, doctors urged that criteria used to detect and evaluate the risk of heart disease among post-menopausal women needed to be expanded to include family history and blood levels of C-reactive protein -- which is linked to vessel inflammation.
Cardiovascular disease is the largest cause of mortality among women, at 38 percent, AHA said.
